  "text": "To determine the distribution of Syt IV, we performed immunoblots of neuronal structures in mouse. Cortex, cerebellum, hippocampus and striatum had very low levels of Syt IV (Fig. 1a) . In contrast, the pituitary yielded a strong signal, consistent with reports of high levels of Syt IV-encoding RNA [CITATION_1] . When the pituitary was separated, strong signals were seen in both the neuro-intermediate lobe (posterior pituitary/neurohypophysis and intermediate lobe) and anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis); the neuro-intermediate lobe contained about four-to eightfold more Syt IV protein than the anterior pituitary (Fig. 1b) . Both posterior and anterior pituitaries from Syt IV knockout mice showed faint background signals resulting from weak crossreactivity of the antibody to Syt IV with another protein of slightly lower molecular mass, which was noted in the manufacturer's data for this reagent.",
